    {
      "explanation": "'Le vin' is masculine, so it takes 'le'. Note that 'rouge' (red) comes after the noun in French — unlike English, where adjectives come before the noun.",
      "sentence": "Le vin rouge est bon",
      "translation": "The red wine is good"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "'Comme dessert' (literally 'as dessert') is how French expresses 'for dessert' when ordering. French uses 'comme' here rather than 'pour' (for), which may surprise English speakers.",
      "sentence": "Comme dessert, je prends une glace",
      "translation": "For dessert, I'll have an ice cream"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "'L'addition' is the word for the restaurant bill/check. The article 'la' becomes 'l'' before a vowel. 's'il vous plaît' (please) uses the formal 'vous' — appropriate with waiters and strangers.",
      "sentence": "L'addition, s'il vous plaît",
      "translation": "The check, please"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "'J'ai faim' literally means 'I have hunger' — French uses 'avoir' (to have) with hunger, unlike English which uses 'to be' ('I am hungry'). This is a key difference to remember.",
      "sentence": "J'ai faim",
      "translation": "I'm hungry"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "'La soupe est chaude' shows adjective agreement: 'chaude' takes a feminine '-e' ending because 'soupe' is feminine. English adjectives never change form for gender.",
      "sentence": "La soupe est chaude",
      "translation": "The soup is hot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "German capitalizes all nouns, so 'Familie' is written with a capital F. 'Meine' agrees with the feminine noun 'Familie', which is why it ends in -e.",
